Distracting waifur's racist father:
I ask you, anon, to give me a little bit more information from your waifur, and develop my plan. A day later, I tell you to tell your waifur to invite her dad along to the Furteenth celebration in Amelie Park this weekend.
The day arrives: a wonderful amount of furries are there in the park, and it's a beautiful summer day. Pleasantly warm, with good sunlight when a cloud doesn't give us temporary respite. I'm behind the grill and I give you, anon, a smile when I see you arrive before waifur and her dad.
"Ayy, glad you're here!" I bring out the steaks, raw and cold in the ziploc bags they're marinating in. "So, as I told you, I'll have you help a little with the cooking, but I can totally handle it." I smile, confident in our plan.
Waifur and her father arrive, and both seem pleased, though dadfur furrows his brows once he sees the few humans around, his fur visibly rising up atop his head. But he doesn't make a scene, and begins conversing with other middle-age anthros there. Waifur smiles a cute, slightly nervous smile at you when she sees you! But she turns away, not letting her father see.
It's time to cook, and we do: I handle the charcoal and thermometers, but I let you place the meat on the park grill while I watch closely. Most furries give us big smiles, excited for the food. Dadfur is avoiding us, for sure, on the further side of the crowd, while waifur is closer, but not the closest. Most anthros have already told us how well they want their meet done, after I hollered out asking people to do so. But dadfur hasn't.
But we know his favorite: waifur told us. Medium. Not medium-rare, not medium-well, but medium. So you and I always make sure one of the pieces of steak is always ready to be taken off medium... even as we prepare the beef for everyone else. I show you that while a meat thermometer really is useful, what really works is making a little cut with a knife and peeking in.

Thank you, I'm glad you like it.
Cooking well mostly just takes experience. Not a huge amount of experience, but you get it over the years (or months!) by looking up cooking topics on Wikipedia, your search engine of choice, and /ck/, and then actually cooking.
The cooking things in the story are:
Thermometers and doneness: turns out how well-done a meat is is based solely on the actual taste, texture, and appearance of the meat. A thermometer can help, but the canon doneness isn't judged by a number. If presentation of the meat is no issue, cutting a piece of meat in half is the easiest way to judge doneness. A side effect is, if your meat is underdone, it'll cook faster after being cut in half.
Doneness and other people: many people think "well-done" means overcooked, and also slide the other labels up a single notch on the doneness scale. At the same time, it's known that most (but not all) cookbooks, over the decades, have altered the numeric temperatures for each level of doneness downward. (i.e. sliding the doneness labels the other direction)
So if you're cooking for someone, it's best to ask him to describe his ideal steak, rather than use a label.
